{"text": "(H25)\n\nNow, note that if we pick \u03c6e\u2212\u03c6o=\u03c0/2, we get that the standing wave contribution cancels out to a constant.\n\nDropping the standing wave contribution, further note that:\n\nVi\n\nm,n+1\u2212Vi\n\nm,n=V0\u0014\n\ncos\u0012n+ 1\n\n2\u03c0+\u03c6i\u0013\n\n\u2212cos\u0010n\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c6i\u0011\u0015\n\ncos\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9it+\u03d5i\u0011\n\n(H26)\n\n=V0h\n\n\u2212sin\u0010n\n\n2\u03c0+\u03c6i\u0011\n\n\u2212cos\u0010n\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c6i\u0011i\n\ncos\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9it+\u03d5i\u0011\n\n(H27)\n\n=\u2212\u221a\n\n2V0sin\u0010n\n\n2\u03c0+\u03c6i+\u03c0\n\n4\u0011\n\ncos\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9it+\u03d5i\u0011\n\n. (H28)\n\nNote that, when \u03c6i=\u03c0/4, then Vi\n\nm,n+1\u2212Vi\n\nm,nwill vanish when nis odd. Conversely, if \u03c6=\u2212\u03c0/4, then Vi\n\nm,n+1\u2212Vi\n\nm,n\n\nwill vanish when nis even. As such, we will pick\n\n\u03c6e=\u03c0/4\u03c6o=\u2212\u03c0/4, (H29)\n\nwhich meets the criteria necessary to cancel out the standing wave contribution. This means that Vi\n\nm,n(t) will address\n\neven and odd bonds separately. Let us compute the zeroth-order term in the Magnus expansion to get the effective\n\nHamiltonian. The full, time-dependent Hamiltonian is given by\n\n\u02c6Hlab,0(t) =\u2212X\n\nm,n\u0010\n\ntx\u02c6c\u2020\n\nm+1,n\u02c6cm,n+ty\u02c6c\u2020\n\nm,n+1\u02c6cm,n+ h.c.\u0011\n\n+X\n\nm,n\u2206n\u02c6nm,n (H30)\n\n+X\n\nm,nX\n\niV0cos\u0010n\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c6i\u0011\n\ncos\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9it+\u03d5i\u0011\n\n\u02c6nm,n. (H31)\n\nNow, we move to a rotating frame via a unitary:\n\n\u02c6U(t) = exp\uf8f1\n\n\uf8f2\n\n\uf8f3\u2212iX\n\nm,nZt\uf8ee\n\n\uf8f0\u2206n+V0X\n\njcos\u0010n\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c6j\u0011\n\ncos\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9jt\u2032+\u03d5j\u0011\uf8f9\n\n\uf8fb\u02c6nm,ndt\u2032\uf8fc\n\n\uf8fd\n\n\uf8fe(H32)\n\n= exp\uf8f1\n\n\uf8f2\n\n\uf8f3\u2212iX\n\nm,n\uf8ee\n\n\uf8f0\u2206nt+X\n\njV0\n\n\u03c9jcos\u0010n\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c6j\u0011\n\nsin\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9jt+\u03d5j\u0011\uf8f9\n\n\uf8fb\u02c6nm,n\uf8fc\n\n\uf8fd\n\n\uf8fe(H33)\n\n= exp(\n\n\u2212iX\n\nm,n\u03c7m,n(t)\u02c6nm,n)\n\n. (H34)\n\n63\n\nThis yields an effective Hamiltonian in the rotating frame given by:\n\n\u02c6H0(t) =\u02c6U\u2020(t)\u02c6H(t)\u02c6U(t)\u2212i\u02c6U\u2020(t)\u2202t\u02c6U(t) (H35)\n\n=\u2212X\n\nn,m\u0010\n\ntxei\u03b7x\n\nm,n(t)\u02c6c\u2020\n\nm+1,n\u02c6cm,n+tyei\u03b7y\n\nm,n(t)\u02c6c\u2020\n\nm,n+1\u02c6cm,n+ h.c\u0011\n\n, (H36)\n\nwhere the absence of the lab subscript on the Hamiltonian indicates that we are in the rotating frame, \u03b7x\n\nm,n=\n\n\u03c7m+1,n\u2212\u03c7m,n, and also \u03b7y\n\nm,n=\u03c7m,n+1\u2212\u03c7m,n. Therefore, we have that:\n\n\u03b7y\n\nm,n=\u03c7m,n+1\u2212\u03c7m,n (H37)\n\n= (\u2206 n+1\u2212\u2206n)t+X\n\njV0\n\n\u03c9j\u0014\n\ncos\u0012(n+ 1)\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c6j\u0013\n\n\u2212cos\u0010n\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c6j\u0011\u0015\n\nsin\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9jt+\u03c6j\u0011\n\n(H38)\n\n= (\u22121)n+1\u2206t\u2212X\n\nj\u221a\n\n2V0\n\n\u03c9jsin\u0010n\n\n2\u03c0+\u03c6j+\u03c0\n\n4\u0011\n\nsin\u0010\n\n\u2212m\u03c0\n\n2+\u03c9jt+\u03d5j\u0011\n\n.", "embedding": [0.0031844808, 0.021013156, 0.017568722, -0.008219346, -0.016901812, -0.0032727264, -0.03297662, 0.0048854495, -0.023471022, 0.08349583, 0.018945526, -0.008994838, -0.005623815, -0.04369726, -0.029666118, 0.034969915, -0.0025228362, -0.017202897, -0.08646804, 0.024649456, 0.03646715, -0.042862162, -0.08013912, -0.028221903, -0.017565401, 0.020875135, 0.015155001, 0.005825395, 0.07075346, 0.016076079, 0.04392037, -0.020102192, 0.0080491, -0.033617914, -0.0112195825, 0.014889667, -0.038986478, -0.018908544, 0.048019823, -0.036264416, 0.057188842, -0.018647678, 0.015804948, -0.025563784, 0.006849719, -0.031275805, -0.021678336, -0.01502921, -0.030557986, -0.051162645, 0.010584374, 0.018603675, 0.044179033, -0.006651223, -0.031025555, 0.018111115, 0.0057248035, 0.02324605